	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>When a strange mechanical sucking creature invades his aquarium, a goldfish must protect the home he loves. That&rsquo;s the premise behind a short film by about two-dozen students in the University of Central Florida&rsquo;s Digital Media Department. Nearly a year-and-a-half in the making, the project&rsquo;s inaugural screening is scheduled for Tuesday evening. <br />
<br />
&ldquo;Atlas&rsquo; Revenge&rdquo; employs some of the latest three-dimensional animation software and modeling techniques to bring a digitized goldfish to &ldquo;life.&rdquo; &ldquo;He has humanistic characteristics that make you relate to the little fish and know what he&rsquo;s feeling,&rdquo; said Darlene Hadrika, who oversaw the film&rsquo;s production as a faculty member in Digital Media&rsquo;s Visual Language track.<br />
<br />
The screening is part of the second Digital Media Premier Gala from 5:30 to 9 p.m. Tuesday, May 5, at the UCF Center for Emerging Media, 500 W. Livingston St., in downtown Orlando.&nbsp; The gala is free and open to the public.<br />
<br />
&ldquo;Atlas&rsquo; Revenge&rdquo; screenings will be at 6:30 and 7: 30 p.m. Other exhibitions include research showcases from digital media undergraduate and graduate students, as well as networking opportunities with local industry representatives and digital media alumni. <br />
<br />
Last year, several students landed jobs as a result of networking with professionals at the gala, Hadrika said. Another handful of students from the program already have job or internship opportunities lined up after this week&rsquo;s graduation. <br />
<br />
The Visual Language track is unique because it encourages collaboration among students and faculty. Students in the program learn not only digital animation, but modeling and other computer programs and skills to be successful in the simulation industry. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re not just teaching students how to make an animated film, but also how to build a model or rig a skeletal structure, and those kind of skills can be hard to find,&rdquo; Hadrika said. <br />
<br />
To teach this, the department established an intensive two-year narrative animation concentration program that gives students the opportunity to develop classic narrative animation techniques in a relatively short time.<br />
<br />
The students work with each other, faculty and guest professionals, such as Pixar Animation Studio layout artist and cinematographer Craig Good, who offered up tips for &ldquo;Atlas&rsquo; Revenge.&rdquo;<br />
<br />
&ldquo;He spent the entire day with the students, going over the film and giving them advice,&rdquo; Hadrika said. <br />
<br />
In all, &ldquo;Atlas&rsquo; Revenge&rdquo; is the work of 25 undergraduate digital media students and one graduate student director. Locally known composer and UCF professor Stella Sung, also in UCF&rsquo;s Digital Media department, wrote the six-minute short&rsquo;s soundtrack. Sung provided the students with the music at the beginning of the project so they could craft the storyline around it. &nbsp;<br />
<br />
Tuesday&rsquo;s gala is sponsored by the Digital Media department, the UCF College of Arts and Humanities, UCF&rsquo;s SIGGRAPH Student Chapter, the Digital Media Club and the UCF Alumni Association's digital media chapter.<br />
<br />
To learn more about &ldquo;Atlas&rsquo; Revenge,&rdquo; go to <a href="http://www.atlasrevenge.com">http://www.atlasrevenge.com</a>. Click <a href="http://www.facebook.com/pages/Atlas-Revenge/66799485054?v=wall&amp;viewas=501031837#/video/video.php?v=718521589862&amp;ref=mf">here</a> to watch the film&rsquo;s trailer on Facebook. <br />
<br />
For more on UCF&rsquo;s Digital Media department and its Visual Language track, visit <a href="http://www.dm.ucf.edu">http://www.dm.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
<hr />
<p><b style="">UCF Stands For Opportunity </b>--The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 5th largest in the nation with more than 50,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
